# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cnc-machining
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] CAM (computer-aided manufacturing), also known as **computer-aided modeling** or **computer-aided machining** is the use of software to control machine tools in the manufacturing of work pieces.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] This is not the only definition for CAM, but it is the most common.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] It may also refer to the use of a computer to assist in all operations of a manufacturing plant, including planning, management, transportation and storage.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Its primary purpose is to create a faster production process and components and tooling with more precise dimensions and material consistency, which in some cases, uses only the required amount of raw material (thus minimizing waste), while simultaneously reducing energy consumption.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] CAM is now a system used in schools and lower educational purposes.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] CAM is a subsequent computer-aided process after computer-aided design (CAD) and sometimes computer-aided engineering (CAE), as the model generated in CAD and verified in CAE can be input into CAM software, which then controls the machine tool.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] CAM is used in many schools alongside CAD to create objects.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Traditionally, CAM has been a numerical control (NC) programming tool, wherein two-dimensional (2-D) or three-dimensional (3-D) models of components are generated in CAD.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] As with other "computer-aided" technologies, CAM does not eliminate the need for skilled professionals such as manufacturing engineers, NC programmers, or machinists.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] CAM leverages both the value of the most skilled manufacturing professionals through advanced productivity tools, while building the skills of new professionals through visualization, simulation and optimization tools.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] A CAM tool generally converts a model to a language the target machine in question understands, typically G-code.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] The numerical control can be applied to machining tools, or more recently to 3D printers.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Early commercial applications of CAM were in large companies in the automotive and aerospace industries; for example, Pierre Bézier's work developing the CAD/CAM application UNISURF in the 1960s for car body design and tooling at Renault.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Alexander Hammer at DeLaval Steam Turbine Company invented a technique to progressively drill turbine blades out of a solid block of metal with the drill controlled by a punch card reader in 1950.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Boeing first obtained NC machines in 1956, made by companies such as Kearney and Trecker, Stromberg-Carlson and Thompson Ramo Wooldridge.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Historically, CAM software was seen to have several shortcomings that necessitated an overly high level of involvement by skilled CNC machinists.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] CAM software would output code for the least capable machine, as each machine tool control added on to the standard G-code set for increased flexibility.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] In some cases, such as improperly set up CAM software or specific tools, the CNC machine required manual editing before the program will run properly.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] None of these issues were so insurmountable that a thoughtful engineer or skilled machine operator could not overcome for prototyping or small production runs; G-Code is a simple language.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] In high production or high precision shops, a different set of problems were encountered where an experienced CNC machinist must both hand-code programs and run CAM software.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] The integration of CAD with other components of CAD/CAM/CAE Product lifecycle management (PLM) environment requires an effective CAD data exchange.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Usually it had been necessary to force the CAD operator to export the data in one of the common data formats, such as IGES or STL or Parasolid formats that are supported by a wide variety of software.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] The output from the CAM software is usually a simple text file of G-code/M-codes, sometimes many thousands of commands long, that is then transferred to a machine tool using a direct numerical control (DNC) program or in modern Controllers using a common USB Storage Device.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] CAM packages could not, and still cannot, reason as a machinist can.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] They could not optimize toolpaths to the extent required of mass production.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Users would select the type of tool, machining process and paths to be used.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] While an engineer may have a working knowledge of G-code programming, small optimization and wear issues compound over time.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Mass-produced items that require machining are often initially created through casting or some other non-machine method.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] This enables hand-written, short, and highly optimized G-code that could not be produced in a CAM package.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] At least in the United States, there is a shortage of young, skilled machinists entering the workforce able to perform at the extremes of manufacturing; high precision and mass production.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] As CAM software and machines become more complicated, the skills required of a machinist or machine operator advance to approach that of a computer programmer and engineer rather than eliminating the CNC machinist from the workforce.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Over time, the historical shortcomings of CAM are being attenuated, both by providers of niche solutions and by providers of high-end solutions.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] For the user who is just getting started as a CAM user, out-of-the-box capabilities providing Process Wizards, templates, libraries, machine tool kits, automated feature based machining and job function specific tailorable user interfaces build user confidence and speed the learning curve.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] User confidence is further built on 3D visualization through a closer integration with the 3D CAD environment, including error-avoiding simulations and optimizations.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] The manufacturing environment is increasingly complex.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] The modern machinery cannot be properly used without this assistance.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Today’s CAM user can easily generate streamlined tool paths, optimized tool axis tilt for higher feed rates, better tool life and surface finish, and ideal cutting depth.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] To ensure ease of use appropriate to user objectives, modern CAM solutions are scalable from a stand-alone CAM system to a fully integrated multi-CAD 3D solution-set.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] These solutions are created to meet the full needs of manufacturing personnel including part planning, shop documentation, resource management and data management and exchange.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Most machining progresses through many stages, each of which is implemented by a variety of basic and sophisticated strategies, depending on the part design, material, and software available.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] , or a rough casting which a CNC machine cuts roughly to shape of the final model, ignoring the fine details.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] or steps, because the strategy has taken multiple "steps" down the part as it removes material.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] This takes the best advantage of the machine's ability by cutting material horizontally.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Common strategies are zig-zag clearing, offset clearing, plunge roughing, rest-roughing, and trochoidal milling (adaptive clearing).
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] The goal at this stage is to remove the most material in the least time, without much concern for overall dimensional accuracy.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] When roughing a part, a small amount of extra material is purposely left behind to be removed in subsequent finishing operation(s).
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] This process begins with a roughed part that unevenly approximates the model and cuts to within a fixed offset distance from the model.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] The semi-finishing pass must leave a small amount of material (called the scallop) so the tool can cut accurately, but not so little that the tool and material deflect away from the cutting surfaces.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Finishing involves many light passes across the material in fine steps to produce the finished part.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] When finishing a part, the steps between passes is minimal to prevent tool deflection and material spring back.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] In order to reduce the lateral tool load, tool engagement is reduced, while feed rates and spindle speeds are generally increased in order to maintain a target surface speed (SFM).
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] A light chip load at high feed and RPM is often referred to as High Speed Machining (HSM), and can provide quick machining times with high quality results.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] In addition to modifying speeds and feeds, machinists will often have finishing specific endmills, which never used as roughing endmills.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] This is done to protect the endmill from developing chips and flaws in the cutting surface, which would leave streaks and blemishes on the final part.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] In milling applications on hardware with rotary table and/or rotary head axes, a separate finishing process called contouring can be performed.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] Instead of stepping down in fine-grained increments to approximate a surface, the work piece or tool is rotated to make the cutting surfaces of the tool tangent to the ideal part features.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] This produces an excellent surface finish with high dimensional accuracy.
[src:cnc-machining/computer-aided-manufacturing] This process is commonly used to machine complex organic shapes such as turbine and impeller blades, which due to their complex curves and overlapping geometry, are impossible to machine with only three axis machines.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] G-code instructions are provided to a machine controller (industrial computer) that tells the motors where to move, how fast to move, and what path to follow.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] The same concept also extends to noncutting tools such as forming or burnishing tools, photoplotting, additive methods such as 3D printing, and measuring instruments.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] The first implementation of a numerical control programming language was developed at the MIT Servomechanisms Laboratory in the 1950s.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] In the decades that followed, many implementations were developed by numerous organizations, both commercial and noncommercial.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] Elements of G-code had often been used in these implementations.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] The first standardized version of G-code used in the United States, *RS-274*, was published in 1963 by the Electronic Industries Alliance (EIA; then known as Electronic Industries Association).
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] In 1974, EIA approved *RS-274-C*, which merged *RS-273* (variable block for positioning and straight cut) and *RS-274-B* (variable block for contouring and contouring/positioning).
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] In other countries, the standard *ISO 6983* (finalized in 1982) is often used, but many European countries use other standards.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] For example, *DIN 66025* is used in Germany, and PN-73M-55256 and PN-93/M-55251 were formerly used in Poland.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] From the 1970s to 1990s, many CNC machine tool builders attempted to overcome compatibility difficulties by standardizing on machine tool controllers built by Fanuc.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] Siemens was another market dominator in CNC controls, especially in Europe.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] In the 2010s, controller differences and incompatibility were mitigated with the widespread adoption of CAD/CAM applications that could output the appropriate G-code to operate a specific machine through a software tool called a post-processor (sometimes shortened to "post").
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] G-code began as a limited language that lacked constructs such as loops, conditional operators, and programmer-declared variables with natural-word-including names (or the expressions in which to use them).
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] It was unable to encode logic but was just a way to "connect the dots" where the programmer figured out many of the dots' locations longhand.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] The latest implementations of G-code include macro language capabilities somewhat closer to a high-level programming language.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] Additionally, all primary manufacturers (e.g., Fanuc, Siemens Digital Industries Software, Heidenhain) provide access to programmable logic controller (PLC) data, such as axis positioning data and tool data, via variables used by NC programs.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] These constructs make it easier to develop automation applications.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] Extensions and variations have been added independently by control manufacturers and machine tool manufacturers, and operators of a specific controller must be aware of the differences between each manufacturer's product.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] One standardized version of G-code, known as *BCL* (Binary Cutter Language), is used only on very few machines.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] Developed at MIT, BCL was developed to control CNC machines in terms of straight lines and arcs.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] Some CNC machines use "conversational" programming, which is a wizard-like programming mode that either hides G-code or completely bypasses the use of G-code.
[src:cnc-machining/g-code] Some popular examples are Okuma's Advanced One Touch (AOT), Southwestern Industries' ProtoTRAK, Mazak's Mazatrol, Hurco's Ultimax and Winmax, Haas' Intuitive Programming System (IPS), and Mori Seiki's CAPS conversational software.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] A **machine tool** is a machine for handling or machining metal or other rigid materials, usually by cutting, boring, grinding, shearing, or other forms of deformations.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Machine tools employ some sort of tool that does the cutting or shaping.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] All machine tools have some means of constraining the workpiece and provide a guided movement of the parts of the machine.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Thus, the relative movement between the workpiece and the cutting tool (which is called the **toolpath**) is controlled or constrained by the machine to at least some extent, rather than being entirely "offhand" or "freehand".
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] It is a power-driven metal cutting machine which assists in managing the needed relative motion between cutting tool and the job that changes the size and shape of the job material.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The precise definition of the term *machine tool* varies among users.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] While all machine tools are "machines that help people to make things", not all factory machines are machine tools.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Today machine tools are typically powered other than by the human muscle (e.g., electrically, hydraulically, or via line shaft), used to make manufactured parts (components) in various ways that include cutting or certain other kinds of deformation.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] With their inherent precision, machine tools enabled the economical production of interchangeable parts.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] In this view of the definition, the term, arising at a time when all tools up till then had been hand tools, simply provided a label for "tools that were machines instead of hand tools".
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] This lathe "produced screw threads out of wood and employed a true compound slide rest".
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] National Bureau of Economic Research (NBER) referenced the definition of a machine tool as "any machine operating by other than hand power which employs a tool to work on metal".
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The narrowest colloquial sense of the term reserves it only for machines that perform metal cutting—in other words, the many kinds of conventional machining and grinding.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] These processes are a type of deformation that produces swarf.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] However, economists use a slightly broader sense that also includes metal deformation of other types that squeeze the metal into shape without cutting off swarf, such as rolling, stamping with dies, shearing, swaging, riveting, and others.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Thus presses are usually included in the economic definition of machine tools.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Many reports on machine tool export and import and similar economic topics use this broader definition.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The colloquial sense implying conventional metal cutting is also growing obsolete because of changing technology over the decades.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] In addition, some of the newly developed additive manufacturing processes, which are not about cutting away material but rather about adding it, are done by machines that are likely to end up labeled, in some cases, as machine tools.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] In fact, machine tool builders are already developing machines that include both subtractive and additive manufacturing in one work envelope, and retrofits of existing machines are underway.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] In modern precision engineering, the accuracy of machine tool components is often maintained through the use of a Hirth joint.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] This coupling is the industry standard for high-accuracy positioning in components such as CNC rotary tables and tool turrets.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Its straight-tooth geometry provides maximum static stiffness and positional repeatability, ensuring that the machine maintains micron-level alignment while resisting heavy cutting forces during the machining process.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Forerunners of machine tools included bow drills and potter's wheels, which had existed in ancient Egypt prior to 2500 BC, and lathes, known to have existed in multiple regions of Europe since at least 1000 to 500 BC.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] But it was not until the later Middle Ages and the Age of Enlightenment that the modern concept of a machine tool—a class of machines used as tools in the making of metal parts, and incorporating machine-guided toolpath—began to evolve.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Clockmakers of the Middle Ages and renaissance men such as Leonardo da Vinci helped expand humans' technological milieu toward the preconditions for industrial machine tools.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] During the 18th and 19th centuries, and even in many cases in the 20th, the builders of machine tools tended to be the same people who would then use them to produce the end products (manufactured goods).
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] However, from these roots also evolved an industry of machine tool builders as we define them today, meaning people who specialize in building machine tools for sale to others.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Historians of machine tools often focus on a handful of major industries that most spurred machine tool development.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Others could be included in this list as well, but they tend to be connected with the root causes already listed.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Machine tools filled a need created by textile machinery during the Industrial Revolution in England in the middle to late 1700s.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Until that time, machinery was made mostly from wood, often including gearing and shafts.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The increase in mechanization required more metal parts, which were usually made of cast iron or wrought iron.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Cast iron could be cast in molds for larger parts, such as engine cylinders and gears, but was difficult to work with a file and could not be hammered.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Red hot wrought iron could be hammered into shapes.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Room temperature wrought iron was worked with a file and chisel and could be made into gears and other complex parts; however, hand working lacked precision and was a slow and expensive process.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] James Watt was unable to have an accurately bored cylinder for his first steam engine, trying for several years until John Wilkinson invented a suitable boring machine in 1774, boring Boulton & Watt's first commercial engine in 1776.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The advance in the accuracy of machine tools can be traced to Henry Maudslay and refined by Joseph Whitworth.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The process by which the master plane gages were produced dates back to antiquity but was refined to an unprecedented degree in the Maudslay shop.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The process begins with three square plates each given an identification (ex., 1,2 and 3).
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The first step is to rub plates 1 and 2 together with a marking medium (called bluing today) revealing the high spots which would be removed by hand scraping with a steel scraper, until no irregularities were visible.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] This would not produce true plane surfaces but a "ball and socket" concave-concave and convex-convex fit, as this mechanical fit, like two perfect planes, can slide over each other and reveal no high spots.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The rubbing and marking are repeated after rotating 2 relative to 1 by 90 degrees to eliminate concave-convex "potato-chip" curvature.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Next, plate number 3 is compared and scraped to conform to plate number 1 in the same two trials.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] In this manner plates number 2 and 3 would be identical.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Next plates number 2 and 3 would be checked against each other to determine what condition existed, either both plates were "balls" or "sockets" or "chips" or a combination.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] These would then be scraped until no high spots existed and then compared to plate number 1.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Repeating this process of comparing and scraping the three plates could produce plane surfaces accurate to within millionths of an inch (the thickness of the marking medium).
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The traditional method of producing the surface gages used an abrasive powder rubbed between the plates to remove the high spots, but it was Whitworth who contributed the refinement of replacing the grinding with hand scraping.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Sometime after 1825, Whitworth went to work for Maudslay and it was there that Whitworth perfected the hand scraping of master surface plane gages.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] With the creation of master plane gages of such high accuracy, all critical components of machine tools (i.e., guiding surfaces such as machine ways) could then be compared against them and scraped to the desired accuracy.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The first machine tools offered for sale (i.e., commercially available) were constructed by Matthew Murray in England around 1800.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Others, such as Henry Maudslay, James Nasmyth, and Joseph Whitworth, soon followed the path of expanding their entrepreneurship from manufactured end products and millwright work into the realm of building machine tools for sale.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Important early machine tools included the slide rest lathe, screw-cutting lathe, turret lathe, milling machine, pattern tracing lathe, shaper, and metal planer, which were all in use before 1840.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] With these machine tools the decades-old objective of producing interchangeable parts was finally realized.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] An important early example of something now taken for granted was the standardization of screw fasteners such as nuts and bolts.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Before about the beginning of the 19th century, these were used in pairs, and even screws of the same machine were generally not interchangeable.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Methods were developed to cut screw thread to a greater precision than that of the feed screw in the lathe being used.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] This led to the bar length standards of the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] American production of machine tools was a critical factor in the Allies' victory in World War II.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Production of machine tools tripled in the United States in the war.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] No war was more industrialized than World War II, and it has been written that the war was won as much by machine shops as by machine guns.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The production of machine tools is concentrated in about 10 countries worldwide: China, Japan, Germany, Italy, South Korea, Taiwan, Switzerland, US, Austria, Spain and a few others.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Machine tool innovation continues in several public and private research centers worldwide.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Machine tools can be powered from a variety of sources.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Human and animal power (via cranks, treadles, treadmills, or treadwheels) were used in the past, as was water power (via water wheel); however, following the development of high-pressure steam engines in the mid 19th century, factories increasingly used steam power.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Factories also used hydraulic and pneumatic power.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Many small workshops continued to use water, human and animal power until electrification after 1900.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Today most machine tools are powered by electricity; hydraulic and pneumatic power are sometimes used, but this is uncommon.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Machine tools can be operated manually, or under automatic control.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Early machines used flywheels to stabilize their motion and had complex systems of gears and levers to control the machine and the piece being worked on.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Soon after World War II, the numerical control (NC) machine was developed.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] NC machines used a series of numbers punched on paper tape or punched cards to control their motion.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] In the 1960s, computers were added to give even more flexibility to the process.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Such machines became known as computerized numerical control (CNC) machines.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] NC and CNC machines could precisely repeat sequences over and over, and could produce much more complex pieces than even the most skilled tool operators.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Before long, the machines could automatically change the specific cutting and shaping tools that were being used.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] For example, a drill machine might contain a magazine with a variety of drill bits for producing holes of various sizes.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Previously, either machine operators would usually have to manually change the bit or move the work piece to another station to perform these different operations.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The next logical step was to combine several different machine tools together, all under computer control.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] These are known as machining centers, and have dramatically changed the way parts are made.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] When fabricating or shaping parts, several techniques are used to remove unwanted metal.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Other techniques are used to *add* desired material.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] Devices that fabricate components by selective *addition* of material are called rapid prototyping machines.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The worldwide market for machine tools was approximately $81 billion in production in 2014 according to a survey by market research firm Gardner Research.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] The largest producer of machine tools was China with $23.8 billion of production followed by Germany and Japan at neck and neck with $12.9 billion and $12.88 billion respectively.
[src:cnc-machining/machine-tool] South Korea and Italy rounded out the top 5 producers with revenue of $5.6 billion and $5 billion respectively.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Machining is a major process of the manufacture of many metal products, but it can also be used on other materials such as wood, plastic, ceramic, and composites.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] A person who specializes in machining is called a machinist.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] As a commercial venture, machining is generally performed in a machine shop, which consists of one or more workrooms containing primary machine tools.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Although a machine shop can be a standalone operation, many businesses maintain internal machine shops or tool rooms that support their specialized needs.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Much modern-day machining uses computer numerical control (CNC), in which computers control the movement and operation of mills, lathes, and other cutting machines.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The precise meaning of the term *machining* has changed over the past one and a half centuries as technology has advanced in a number of ways.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] In the 18th century, the word *machinist* meant a person who built or repaired machines.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] This person's work was primarily done by hand, using processes such as the carving of wood and the writing-forging and hand-filing of metal.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] At the time, millwrights and builders of new kinds of *engines* (meaning, more or less, machines of any kind), such as James Watt or John Wilkinson, would fit the definition.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The noun *machine tool* and the verb *to machine* (*machined, machining*) did not yet exist.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Around the middle of the 20th century, the latter words were coined as the concepts they described evolved into widespread existence.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Therefore, during the Machine Age, *machining* referred to (what we today might call) the "traditional" machining processes, such as turning, boring, drilling, milling, broaching, sawing, shaping, planing, abrasive cutting, reaming, and tapping.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] In these "traditional" or "conventional" machining processes, machine tools, such as lathes, milling machines, drill presses, or others, are used with a sharp cutting tool to remove material to achieve a desired geometry.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Currently, "machining" without qualification usually implies the traditional machining processes.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The two terms are effectively synonymous, although the long-established usage of the term *machining* continues.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] This is comparable to the idea that the verb sense of *contact* evolved because of the proliferation of ways to contact someone (telephone, email, IM, SMS, and so on) but did not entirely replace the earlier terms such as *call*, *talk to*, or *write to*.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Machining is any process in which a cutting tool removes material from the workpiece (the workpiece is often called the "work").
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Relative motion is required in traditional machining between the device and the work to remove material; non-traditional machining processes use other methods of material removal, such as electric current in EDM (electro-discharge machining).
[src:cnc-machining/machining] This relative motion is achieved in most machining operations by moving (by lateral rotary or lateral motion) either the tool, or the workpiece.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The shape of the tool, the relative motion, and its penetration into the work, produce the desired shape of the resulting work surface.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Machining operations can be broken down into traditional, and non-traditional operations.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Within the traditional operations, there are two categories of machining based on the shape they machine; being circular shapes that includes; turning, boring, drilling, reaming, threading and more, and various/straight shapes that includes; milling, broaching, sawing, grinding and shaping.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] A cutting tool has one or more sharp cutting edges and is made of a harder material than the work material.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The cutting edge serves to separate the chip from the parent work material.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The rake face, which directs the flow of the newly formed chip, is oriented at a certain angle and is called the rake angle "α." It is measured relative to the plane perpendicular to the work surface.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The rake angle can be positive or negative.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The flank of the tool provides a clearance between the tool and the newly formed work surface, thus protecting the surface from abrasion, which would degrade the finish.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] This angle between the work and flank surfaces is called the relief angle.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] A single-point tool has one cutting edge for turning, boring, and planing.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] During machining, the device's point penetrates below the work part's original work surface.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The fact is sometimes rounded to a certain radius, called the nose radius.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Multiple cutting-edge tools have more than one cutting edge and usually achieve their motion relative to the work part by rotating.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Drilling and milling use turning multiple-cutting-edge tools.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Although the shapes of these tools are different from a single-point device, many elements of tool geometry are similar.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Chip formation during machining results from severe plastic deformation of the material in the primary shear zone ahead of the cutting tool.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The morphology and fragmentation of chips depend on cutting parameters, tool geometry, and the microstructure of the workpiece material.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Continuous, segmented, or discontinuous chips may form depending on the mechanical properties and deformation mechanisms of the metal being machined.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The morphology and fragmentation of chips formed during machining are strongly influenced by the microstructure of steels and by environmental factors such as hydrogen absorption.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Hydrogen can accumulate at lattice defects and alter localized plastic deformation processes in the cutting zone, affecting chip segmentation and the formation of microcracks in the surface layer.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] An unfinished workpiece requiring machining must have some material cut away to create a finished product.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] A finished product would be a workpiece that meets the specifications set out for that workpiece by engineering drawings or blueprints.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] For example, a workpiece may require a specific outside diameter.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] A lathe is a machine tool that can create that diameter by rotating a metal workpiece so that a cutting tool can cut metal away, creating a smooth, round surface matching the required diameter and surface finish.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] A drill can remove the metal in the shape of a cylindrical hole.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Other tools that may be used for metal removal are milling machines, saws, and grinding machines.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Many of these same techniques are used in woodworking.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Machining requires attention to many details for a workpiece to meet the specifications in the engineering drawings or blueprints.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Besides the obvious problems related to correct dimensions, there is the problem of achieving the right finish or surface smoothness on the workpiece.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The inferior finish found on the machined surface of a workpiece may be caused by incorrect clamping, a dull tool, or inappropriate presentation of a device.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Frequently, this poor surface finish, known as chatter, is evident by an undulating or regular finish of waves on the machined surfaces of the workpiece.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Relative motion is required between the tool and work to perform a machining operation.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The primary action is at a specific cutting speed.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] In addition, the device must be moved laterally across the work.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] This is a much slower motion called the feed.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] The remaining dimension of the cut is the penetration of the cutting tool below the original work surface, reaching the cut's depth.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Speed, feed, and depth of cut are called the cutting conditions.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Roughing cuts are used to remove a large amount of material from the starting work part as rapidly as possible, i.e., with a significant Material Removal Rate (MRR), to produce a shape close to the desired form but leaving some material on the piece for a subsequent finishing operation.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Finishing cuts complete the part and achieve the final dimension, tolerances, and surface finish.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] In production machining jobs, one or more roughing cuts are usually performed on the work, followed by one or two finishing cuts.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Roughing operations are done at high feeds and depths – feeds of 0.4–1.25 mm/rev (0.015–0.050 in/rev) and depths of 2.5–20 mm (0.100–0.750 in) are typical, but actual values depend on the workpiece materials.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Cutting speeds are lower in roughing than in finishing.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] A cutting fluid is often applied to the machining operation to cool and lubricate the cutting tool.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Determining whether a cutting fluid should be used and, if so, choosing the proper cutting fluid is usually included within the scope of the cutting condition.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Today other forms of metal cutting are becoming increasingly popular.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] An example of this is water jet cutting.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Water jet cutting involves pressurized water over 620 MPa (90,000 psi) and can cut metal and have a finished product.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] This process is called cold cutting, which eliminates the damage caused by a heat-affected zone, as opposed to laser and plasma cutting.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] With the recent proliferation of additive manufacturing technologies, conventional machining has been retronymously classified, in thought and language, as a subtractive manufacturing method.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] In narrow contexts, additive and subtractive methods may compete with each other.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] In the broad context of entire industries, their relationship is complementary.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] Each method has its advantages over the other.
[src:cnc-machining/machining] While additive manufacturing methods can produce very intricate prototype designs impossible to replicate by machining, strength and material selection may be limited.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling can be done with a wide range of machine tools.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The original class of machine tools for milling was the milling machine (often called a mill).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] After the advent of computer numerical control (CNC) in the 1960s, milling machines evolved into *machining centers*: milling machines augmented by automatic tool changers, tool magazines or carousels, CNC capability, coolant systems, and enclosures.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling centers are generally classified as vertical machining centers (VMCs) or horizontal machining centers (HMCs).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The integration of milling into turning environments, and vice versa, began with live tooling for lathes and the occasional use of mills for turning operations.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This led to a new class of machine tools, multitasking machines (MTMs), which are purpose-built to facilitate milling and turning within the same work envelope.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling is a cutting process that uses a milling cutter to remove material from the surface of a workpiece.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The milling cutter is a rotary cutting tool, often with multiple cutting points.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] As opposed to drilling, where the tool is advanced along its rotation axis, the cutter in milling is usually moved perpendicular to its axis so that cutting occurs on the circumference of the cutter.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] As the milling cutter enters the work piece, the cutting edges (flutes or teeth) of the tool repeatedly cut into and exit from the material, shaving off chips (swarf) from the work piece with each pass.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The cutting action is shear deformation; material is pushed off the work piece in tiny clumps that hang together to a greater or lesser extent (depending on the material) to form chips.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This makes metal cutting somewhat different (in its mechanics) from slicing softer materials with a blade.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The milling process removes material by performing many separate, small cuts.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This is accomplished by using a cutter with many teeth, spinning the cutter at high speed, or advancing the material through the cutter slowly; most often it is some combination of these three approaches.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The speeds and feeds used are varied to suit a combination of variables.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The speed at which the piece advances through the cutter is called **feed rate**, or just **feed**; it is most often measured as distance per time (inches per minute [in/min or ipm] or millimeters per minute [mm/min]), although distance per revolution or per cutter tooth are also sometimes used.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Many different types of cutting tools are used in the milling process.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling cutters such as end mills may have cutting surfaces across their entire end surface, so that they can be drilled into the work piece (plunging).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling cutters may also have extended cutting surfaces on their sides to allow for peripheral milling.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Tools optimized for face milling tend to have only small cutters at their end corners.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The cutting surfaces of a milling cutter are generally made of a hard and temperature-resistant material, so that they wear slowly.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A low cost cutter may have surfaces made of high speed steel.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] More expensive but slower-wearing materials include cemented carbide.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Thin film coatings may be applied to decrease friction or further increase hardness.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] There are cutting tools typically used in milling machines or machining centers to perform milling operations (and occasionally in other machine tools).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] They remove material by their movement within the machine (e.g., a ball nose mill) or directly from the cutter's shape (e.g., a form tool such as a hobbing cutter).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] As material passes through the cutting area of a milling machine, the blades of the cutter take swarfs of material at regular intervals.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Surfaces cut by the side of the cutter (as in peripheral milling) therefore always contain regular ridges.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The distance between ridges and the height of the ridges depend on the feed rate, number of cutting surfaces, the cutter diameter.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] With a narrow cutter and rapid feed rate, these revolution ridges can be significant variations in the surface finish.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The face milling process can in principle produce very flat surfaces.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] However, in practice the result always shows visible trochoidal marks following the motion of points on the cutter's end face.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] These **revolution marks** give the characteristic finish of a face milled surface.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Revolution marks can have significant roughness depending on factors such as flatness of the cutter's end face and the degree of perpendicularity between the cutter's rotation axis and feed direction.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Often a final pass with a slow feed rate is used to improve the surface finish after the bulk of the material has been removed.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In a precise face milling operation, the revolution marks will only be microscopic scratches due to imperfections in the cutting edge.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Gang milling was especially important before the CNC era, because for duplicate part production, it was a substantial efficiency improvement over manual-milling one feature at an operation, then changing machines (or changing setup of the same machine) to cut the next op.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Today, CNC mills with automatic tool change and 4- or 5-axis control obviate gang-milling practice to a large extent.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling is performed with a milling cutter in various forms, held in a collet or similar which, in turn, is held in the spindle of a milling machine.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Mill orientation is the primary classification for milling machines.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The two basic configurations are vertical and horizontal – referring to the orientation of the rotating spindle upon which the cutter is mounted.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] However, there are alternative classifications according to method of control, size, purpose and power source.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In the **vertical milling machine** the spindle axis is vertically oriented.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling cutters are held in the spindle and rotate on its axis.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The spindle can generally be lowered (or the table can be raised, giving the same relative effect of bringing the cutter closer or deeper into the work), allowing plunge cuts and drilling.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The depth to which blades cut into the work can be controlled with a micrometer adjustment nut.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] There are two subcategories of vertical mills: the bed mill and the turret mill.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Turret mills are generally considered by some to be more versatile of the two designs.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A third type also exists, a lighter, more versatile machine, called a mill-drill.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The mill-drill is a close relative of the vertical mill and quite popular in light industry; and with hobbyists.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A mill-drill is similar in basic configuration to a very heavy drill press, but equipped with an X-Y table and a much larger column.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] They also typically use more powerful motors than a comparably sized drill press, most are multi-speed belt driven with some models having a geared head or electronic speed control.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] They generally have quite heavy-duty spindle bearings to deal with the lateral loading on the spindle that is created by a milling operation.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A mill drill also typically raises and lowers the entire head, including motor, often on a dovetailed (sometimes round with rack and pinion) vertical column.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A mill drill also has a large quill that is generally locked during milling operations and released to facilitate drilling functions.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Aside from size, the principal difference between these lighter machines and larger vertical mills is that the X-Y table is at a fixed elevation; the Z-axis is controlled by moving the head or quill down toward the X,Y table.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A mill drill typically has an internal taper fitting in the quill to take a collet chuck, face mills, or a Jacobs chuck similar to the vertical mill.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A horizontal mill has the same short but the cutters are mounted on a horizontal spindle, or arbor, mounted across the table.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Many horizontal mills also feature a built-in rotary table that allows milling at various angles; this feature is called a *universal table*.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] While endmills and the other types of tools available to a vertical mill may be used in a horizontal mill, their real advantage lies in arbor-mounted cutters, called side and face mills, which have a cross section rather like a circular saw, but are generally wider and smaller in diameter.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Because the cutters have good support from the arbor and have a larger cross-sectional area than an end mill, quite heavy cuts can be taken enabling rapid material removal rates.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] These are used to mill grooves and slots.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Plain mills are used to shape flat surfaces.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Several cutters may be ganged together on the arbor to mill a complex shape of slots and planes.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Special cutters can also cut grooves, bevels, radii, or indeed any section desired.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] These specialty cutters tend to be expensive.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Simplex mills have one spindle, and duplex mills have two.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] It is also easier to cut gears on a horizontal mill.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Some horizontal milling machines are equipped with a power-take-off provision on the table.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This allows the table feed to be synchronized to a rotary fixture, enabling the milling of spiral features such as hypoid gears.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A universal milling machine is one with the facility to either have a horizontal spindle or a vertical spindle.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The latter sometimes being on a two-axis turret enabling the spindle to be pointed in any direction one desires.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The two options may be driven independently or from one motor through gearing.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In either case, as the work is generally placed in the same place for either type of operation, the mechanism for the method not being used is moved out of the way.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In smaller machines, "spares" may be lifted off while larger machines offer a system to retract those parts not in use.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The choice between vertical and horizontal spindle orientation in milling machine design usually hinges on the shape and size of a workpiece and the number of sides of the workpiece that require machining.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Work in which the spindle's axial movement is normal to one plane, with an endmill as the cutter, lends itself to a vertical mill, where the operator can stand before the machine and have easy access to the cutting action by looking down upon it.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Thus vertical mills are most favored for diesinking work (machining a mould into a block of metal).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Heavier and longer workpieces lend themselves to placement on the table of a horizontal mill.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Prior to numerical control, horizontal milling machines evolved first, because they evolved by putting milling tables under lathe-like headstocks.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Vertical mills appeared in subsequent decades, and accessories in the form of add-on heads to change horizontal mills to vertical mills (and later vice versa) have been commonly used.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Even in the CNC era, a heavy workpiece needing machining on multiple sides lends itself to a horizontal machining center, while diesinking lends itself to a vertical one.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A milling machine is often called a **mill** by machinists.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The archaic term **miller** was commonly used in the 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Since the 1960s there has developed an overlap of usage between the terms **milling machine** and **machining center**.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] NC/CNC machining centers evolved from milling machines, which is why the terminology evolved gradually with considerable overlap that still persists.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The distinction, when one is made, is that a machining center is a mill with features that pre-CNC mills never had, especially an automatic tool changer (ATC) that includes a tool magazine (carousel), and sometimes an automatic pallet changer (APC).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In typical usage, all machining centers are mills, but not all mills are machining centers; only mills with ATCs are machining centers.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Lathes are available with milling attachments from the manufacturer and from the aftermarket.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Lathe manufacturers publish instructions for milling.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Similar to a milling machine, a collet in the spindle taper (possibly reduced/adapted to the collet series size) holds the tool, and the workpiece is held by the milling attachment.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The carriage then acts as the knee in a milling machine, and the carriage lock tightened to secure the Z-axis.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Most CNC milling machines (also called *machining centers*) are computer controlled vertical mills with the ability to move the spindle vertically along the Z-axis.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This extra degree of freedom permits their use in diesinking, engraving applications, and 2.5D surfaces such as relief sculptures.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] When combined with the use of conical tools or a ball nose cutter, it also significantly improves milling precision without impacting speed, providing a cost-efficient alternative to most flat-surface hand-engraving work.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] CNC machines can exist in virtually any of the forms of manual machinery, like horizontal mills.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The most advanced CNC milling-machines, the multiaxis machine, add two more axes in addition to the three normal axes (XYZ).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Horizontal milling machines also have a C or Q axis, allowing the horizontally mounted workpiece to be rotated, essentially allowing asymmetric and eccentric turning.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The fifth axis (B axis) controls the tilt of the tool itself.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] When all of these axes are used in conjunction with each other, extremely complicated geometries, even organic geometries such as a human head can be made with relative ease with these machines.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] But the skill to program such geometries is beyond that of most operators.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Therefore, 5-axis milling machines are practically always programmed with CAM.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The operating system of such machines is a closed loop system and functions on feedback.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] These machines have developed from the basic NC (NUMERIC CONTROL) machines.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A computerized form of NC machines is known as CNC machines.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A set of instructions (called a program) is used to guide the machine for desired operations.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] There are over 100 different G-codes and M-codes.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A CNC machine is operated by a single operator called a programmer.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This machine is capable of performing various operations automatically and economically.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] With the declining price of computers and open source CNC software, the entry price of CNC machines has plummeted.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The accessories and cutting tools used on machine tools (including milling machines) are referred to in aggregate by the mass noun "tooling".
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] There is a high degree of standardization of the tooling used with CNC milling machines, and a lesser degree with manual milling machines.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] To ease up the organization of the tooling in CNC production many companies use a tool management solution.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling cutters for specific applications are held in various tooling configurations.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] CNC milling machines nearly always use SK (or ISO), CAT, BT or HSK tooling.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] SK tooling is the most common in Europe, while CAT tooling, sometimes called V-Flange Tooling, is the oldest and probably most common type in the USA.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] CAT tooling was invented by Caterpillar Inc. of Peoria, Illinois, in order to standardize the tooling used on their machinery.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] CAT tooling comes in a range of sizes designated as CAT-30, CAT-40, CAT-50, etc.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The number refers to the Association for Manufacturing Technology (formerly the National Machine Tool Builders Association (NMTB)) taper size of the tool.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] An improvement on CAT Tooling is Bridgeport Taper (BT) Tooling, which looks similar and can easily be confused with CAT tooling.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Like CAT Tooling, BT Tooling comes in a range of sizes and uses the same NMTB body taper.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] However, BT tooling is symmetrical about the spindle axis, which CAT tooling is not.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This gives BT tooling greater stability and balance at high speeds.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] One other subtle difference between these two toolholders is the thread used to hold the pull stud.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] CAT Tooling is all Imperial thread and BT Tooling is all Metric thread.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Note that this affects the pull stud only; it does not affect the tool that they can hold.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Both types of tooling are sold to accept both Imperial and metric sized tools.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] SK and HSK tooling, sometimes called "Hollow Shank Tooling", is much more common in Europe where it was invented than it is in the United States.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] It is claimed that HSK tooling is even better than BT Tooling at high speeds.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The holding mechanism for HSK tooling is placed within the (hollow) body of the tool and, as spindle speed increases, it expands, gripping the tool more tightly with increasing spindle speed.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] There is no pull stud with this type of tooling.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] For manual milling machines, there is less standardization, because a greater plurality of formerly competing standards exist.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Newer and larger manual machines usually use NMTB tooling.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This tooling is somewhat similar to CAT tooling but requires a drawbar within the milling machine.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Furthermore, there are a number of variations with NMTB tooling that make interchangeability troublesome.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The older a machine, the greater the plurality of standards that may apply (e.g., Morse, Jarno, Brown & Sharpe, Van Norman, and other less common builder-specific tapers).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] However, two standards that have seen especially wide usage are the Morse #2 and the R8, whose prevalence was driven by the popularity of the mills built by Bridgeport Machines of Bridgeport, Connecticut.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] These mills so dominated the market for such a long time that "Bridgeport" is virtually synonymous with "manual milling machine".
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Most of the machines that Bridgeport made between 1938 and 1965 used a Morse taper #2, and from about 1965 onward most used an R8 taper.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Many cutting tools exist for milling machines, including milling cutters, slitting cutters, gear cutters, end mills, etc.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In this approach, the tool movement is unidirectional.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Zig-zag and zig tool paths are examples of linear tool paths.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In zig-zag milling, material is removed both in forward and backward paths.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In this case, cutting is done both with and against the rotation of the spindle.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This reduces the machining time but increases machine chatter and tool wear.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In zig milling, the tool moves only in one direction.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The tool has to be lifted and retracted after each cut, due to which machining time increases.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] However, in case of zig milling surface quality is better.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In this approach, tool movement is multi-directional.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] One example of non-linear tool path is contour-parallel tool path.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In this approach, the required pocket boundary is used to derive the tool path.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In this case, the cutter is always in contact with the work material.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Hence the idle time spent in positioning and retracting the tool is avoided.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] For large-scale material removal, contour-parallel tool path is widely used because it can be consistently used with up-cut or down-cut method during the entire process.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] There are three different approaches that fall into the category of contour-parallel tool path generation.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In this approach, the tool travels along a gradually evolving spiral path.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The spiral starts at the center of the pocket to be machined and the tool gradually moves towards the pocket boundary.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The direction of the tool path changes progressively and local acceleration and deceleration of the tool are minimized.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling machines evolved from the practice of rotary filing—that is, running a circular cutter with file-like teeth in the headstock of a lathe.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Rotary filing and, later, true milling were developed to reduce time and effort spent hand-filing.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The full story of milling machine development may never be known, because much early development took place in individual shops where few records were kept for posterity.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] However, the broad outlines are known, as summarized below.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] From a history-of-technology viewpoint, it is clear that the naming of this new type of machining with the term "milling" was an extension from that word's earlier senses of processing materials by abrading them in some way (cutting, grinding, crushing, etc.).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A rotary file by Jacques de Vaucanson, circa 1760, is well known.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In 1783, Samuel Rehe invented a true milling machine.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In 1795, Eli Terry began using a milling machine at Plymouth Connecticut in the production of tall case clocks.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] With the use of his milling machine, Terry was the first to accomplish Interchangeable parts in the clock industry.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling wooden parts was efficient in interchangeable parts, but inefficient in high yields.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Milling wooden blanks results in a low yield of parts because the machines single blade would cause loss of gear teeth when the cutter hit parallel grains in the wood.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Terry later invented a spindle cutting machine to mass-produce parts in 1807.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Other Connecticut clockmakers like James Harrison of Waterbury, Thomas Barnes of Litchfield, and Gideon Roberts of Bristol, also used milling machines to produce their clocks.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] It is clear that milling machines as a distinct class of machine tool (separate from lathes running rotary files) first appeared between 1814 and 1818.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The centers of earliest development of true milling machines were two federal armories of the U.S.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] (Springfield and Harpers Ferry) together with the various private armories and inside contractors that shared turnover of skilled workmen with them.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Roe, a respected founding father of machine tool historians, credited Eli Whitney (one of the private arms makers mentioned above) with producing the first true milling machine.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] By 1918, he considered it "Probably the first milling machine ever built—certainly the oldest now in existence […]." However, subsequent scholars, including Robert S.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Woodbury and others, have improved upon Roe's early version of the history and suggest that just as much credit—in fact, probably more—belongs to various other inventors, including Robert Johnson of Middletown, Connecticut; Captain John H.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Hall of the Harpers Ferry armory; Simeon North of the Staddle Hill factory in Middletown; Roswell Lee of the Springfield armory; and Thomas Blanchard.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] (Several of the men mentioned above are sometimes described on the internet as "the inventor of the first milling machine" or "the inventor of interchangeable parts".
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Battison's article "Eli Whitney and the Milling Machine," which was published in the *Smithsonian Journal of History* in 1966, exemplifies the dispelling of the "Great Man" image of Whitney by historians of technology working in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] James Nasmyth built a milling machine very advanced for its time between 1829 and 1831.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] It was tooled to mill the six sides of a hex nut that was mounted in a six-way indexing fixture.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] A milling machine built and used in the shop of Gay & Silver (aka Gay, Silver, & Co) in the 1830s was influential because it employed a better method of vertical positioning than earlier machines.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] For example, Whitney's machine (the one that Roe considered the very first) and others did not make provision for vertical travel of the knee.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Evidently, the workflow assumption behind this was that the machine would be set up with shims, vise, etc. for a certain part design, and successive parts did not require vertical adjustment (or at most would need only shimming).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This indicates that early thinking about milling machines was as production and not as toolroom machines.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In these early years, milling was often viewed as only a roughing operation to be followed by finishing with a hand file.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The idea of *reducing* hand filing was more important than *replacing* it.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Some of the key men in milling machine development during this era included Frederick W.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] (These same men during the same era were also busy developing the state of the art in turret lathes.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Howe's experience at Gay & Silver in the 1840s acquainted him with early versions of both machine tools.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] It took its name from the first company to put one on the market, George S.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Lincoln & Company (formerly the Phoenix Iron Works), whose first one was built in 1855 for the Colt armory.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Vertical positioning ideas were either absent or underdeveloped.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The Lincoln miller's spindle could be raised and lowered, but the original idea behind its positioning was to be set up in position and then run, as opposed to being moved frequently while running.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Like a turret lathe, it was a repetitive-production machine, with each skilled setup followed by extensive fairly low skill operation.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Howe, while working for the Providence Tool Company, asked Joseph R.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Brown of Brown & Sharpe for a solution to the problem of milling spirals, such as the flutes of twist drills.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] These were usually filed by hand at the time.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] (Helical planing existed but was by no means common.) Brown designed a "universal milling machine" that, starting from its first sale in March 1862, was wildly successful.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] It solved the problem of 3-axis travel (i.e., the axes that we now call XYZ) much more elegantly than had been done in the past, and it allowed for the milling of spirals using an indexing head fed in coordination with the table feed.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The term "universal" was applied to it because it was ready for any kind of work, including toolroom work, and was not as limited in application as previous designs.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Brown also developed and patented (1864) the design of formed milling cutters in which successive sharpenings of the teeth do not disturb the geometry of the form.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The advances of the 1860s opened the floodgates and ushered in modern milling practice.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In these decades, Brown & Sharpe and the Cincinnati Milling Machine Company dominated the American milling machine field.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] However, hundreds of other firms also built milling machines at the time, and many were significant in various ways.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Besides a wide variety of specialized production machines, the archetypal multipurpose milling machine of the late 19th and early 20th centuries was a heavy knee-and-column horizontal-spindle design with power table feeds, indexing head, and a stout overarm to support the arbor.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The evolution of machine design was driven not only by inventive spirit but also by the constant evolution of milling cutters that saw milestone after milestone from 1860 through World War I.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Around the end of World War I, machine tool control advanced in various ways that laid the groundwork for later CNC technology.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Shaw was applied to Keller tracer milling machines for die sinking via the three dimensional copying of a template.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This made die sinking faster and easier just as dies were in higher demand than ever before, and was very helpful for large steel dies such as those used to stamp sheets in automobile manufacturing.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Such machines translated the tracer movements to input for servos that worked the machine leadscrews or hydraulics.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] They also spurred the development of antibacklash leadscrew nuts.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] All of the above concepts were new in the 1920s but became routine in the NC/CNC era.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] By the 1930s, incredibly large and advanced milling machines existed, such as the Cincinnati Hydro-Tel, that presaged today's CNC mills in every respect except for CNC control itself.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In 1936, Rudolph Bannow (1897–1962) conceived of a major improvement to the milling machine.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] His company commenced manufacturing a new knee-and-column vertical mill in 1938.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] This was the Bridgeport milling machine, often called a ram-type or turret-type mill because its head has sliding-ram and rotating-turret mounting.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The machine became so popular that many other manufacturers created copies and variants.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Furthermore, its name came to connote any such variant.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The Bridgeport offered enduring advantages over previous models.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] It was small enough, light enough, and affordable enough to be a practical acquisition for even the smallest machine shop businesses, yet it was also smartly designed, versatile, well-built, and rigid.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Its various directions of sliding and pivoting movement allowed the head to approach the work from any angle.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The Bridgeport's design became the dominant form for manual milling machines used by several generations of small- and medium-enterprise machinists.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] By the 1980s an estimated quarter-million Bridgeport milling machines had been built, and they (and their clones) are still being produced today.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] By 1940, automation via cams, such as in screw machines and automatic chuckers, had already been very well developed for decades.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Beginning in the 1930s, ideas involving servomechanisms had been in the air, but it was especially during and immediately after World War II that they began to germinate (see also Numerical control > History).
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] These were soon combined with the emerging technology of digital computers.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Sufficient R&D spending probably would not have happened within the machine tool industry alone; but it was for the latter applications that the will and ability to spend was available.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Once the development was underway, it was eagerly applied to machine tool control in one of the many post-WWII instances of technology transfer.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In 1952, numerical control reached the developmental stage of laboratory reality.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The first NC machine tool was a Cincinnati Hydrotel milling machine retrofitted with a scratch-built NC control unit.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] It was reported in *Scientific American*, just as another groundbreaking milling machine, the Brown & Sharpe universal, had been in 1862.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] During the 1950s, numerical control moved slowly from the laboratory into commercial service.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] For its first decade, it had rather limited impact outside of aerospace work.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] NC and CNC's drastic advancement of machine tool control deeply transformed the culture of manufacturing.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The details (which are beyond the scope of this article) have evolved immensely with every passing decade.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Computers and CNC machine tools continue to develop rapidly.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] The personal computer revolution has a great impact on this development.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] By the late 1980s small machine shops had desktop computers and CNC machine tools.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Soon after, hobbyists, artists, and designers began obtaining CNC mills and lathes.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Manufacturers have started producing economically priced CNCs machines small enough to sit on a desktop which can cut at high resolution materials softer than stainless steel.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] They can be used to make anything from jewelry to printed circuit boards to gun parts, even fine art.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] National and international standards are used to standardize the definitions, environmental requirements, and test methods used for milling.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] Selection of the standard to be used is an agreement between the supplier and the user and has some significance in the design of the mill.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] In the United States, ASME has developed the standards B5.45-1972 *Milling Machines* and B94.19-1997 *Milling Cutters and End Mills*.
[src:cnc-machining/milling-machining] General tolerances include: +/-0.005" (~0.1mm) for local tolerances across most geometries, +/-0.010" (~0.25mm) for plastics with variation depending on the size of the part, 0.030" (~0.75mm) minimum wall thickness for metals, and 0.060" (~1.5mm) minimum wall thickness for plastics.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] A CNC machine is a motorized maneuverable tool and often a motorized maneuverable platform, which are both controlled by a computer, according to specific input instructions.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Instructions are delivered to a CNC machine in the form of a sequential program of machine control instructions such as G-code and M-code, and then executed.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The program can be written by a person or, far more often, generated by graphical computer-aided design (CAD) or computer-aided manufacturing (CAM) software.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] In the case of 3D printers, the part to be printed is cross-sectioned into virtual "slices" before the instructions (or the program) are generated.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] CNC offers greatly increased productivity over non-computerized machining for repetitive production, where the machine must be manually controlled (e.g. using devices such as hand wheels or levers) or mechanically controlled by pre-fabricated pattern guides (see pantograph mill).
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] However, these advantages come at significant cost in terms of both capital expenditure and job setup time.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] For some prototyping and small batch jobs, a good machine operator can have parts finished to a high standard whilst a CNC workflow is still in setup.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] In modern CNC systems, the design of a mechanical part and its manufacturing program are highly automated.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The part's mechanical dimensions are defined using CAD software and then translated into manufacturing directives by CAM software.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The resulting directives are transformed (by "post processor" software) into the specific commands necessary for a particular machine to produce the component and then are loaded into the CNC machine.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Since any particular component might require the use of several different tools – drills, saws, touch probes etc. – modern machines often combine multiple tools into a single "cell".
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] In other installations, several different machines are used with an external controller and human or robotic operators that move the component from machine to machine.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] In either case, the series of steps needed to produce any part is highly automated and produces a part that meets every specification in the original CAD drawing, where each specification includes a tolerance.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] In numerical control systems, the position of the tool is defined by a set of instructions called the part program.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Positioning control is handled using either an open-loop or a closed-loop system.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] In an open-loop system, communication takes place in one direction only: from the controller to the motor.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] In a closed-loop system, feedback is provided to the controller so that it can correct for errors in position, velocity, and acceleration, which can arise due to variations in load or temperature.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Open-loop systems are generally cheaper but less accurate.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Stepper motors can be used in both types of systems, while servo motors can only be used in closed systems.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Motion is controlling multiple axes, normally at least two (X and Y), and a tool spindle that moves in the Z (depth).
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The position of the tool is driven by direct-drive stepper motors or servo motors to provide highly accurate movements, or in older designs, motors through a series of step-down gears.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Open-loop control works as long as the forces are kept small enough and speeds are not too great.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] On commercial metalworking machines, closed-loop controls are standard and required to provide the accuracy, speed, and repeatability demanded.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The G & M code positions are all based on a three-dimensional Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] This system is a typical plane often seen in mathematics when graphing.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] This system is required to map out the machine tool paths and any other kind of actions that need to happen in a specific coordinate.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Absolute coordinates are what are generally used more commonly for machines and represent the (0,0,0) point on the plane.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] This point is set on the stock material to give a starting point or "home position" before starting the actual machining.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] As the controller hardware evolved, the mills themselves also evolved.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] One change has been to enclose the entire mechanism in a large box as a safety measure (with safety glass in the doors to permit the operator to monitor the machine's function), often with additional safety interlocks to ensure the operator is far enough from the working piece for safe operation.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Most new CNC systems built today are 100% electronically controlled.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] CNC-like systems are used for any process that can be described as movements and operations.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] These include laser cutting, welding, friction stir welding, ultrasonic welding, flame and plasma cutting, bending, spinning, hole-punching, pinning, gluing, fabric cutting, sewing, tape and fiber placement, routing, picking and placing, and sawing.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] A mild crash may not damage the machine or tools but may damage the part being machined so that it must be scrapped.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Many CNC tools have no inherent sense of the absolute position of the table or tools when turned on.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] They must be manually "homed" or "zeroed" to have any reference to work from, and these limits are just for figuring out the location of the part to work with it and are no hard motion limit on the mechanism.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] It is often possible to drive the machine outside the physical bounds of its drive mechanism, resulting in a collision with itself or damage to the drive mechanism.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Many machines implement control parameters limiting axis motion past a certain limit in addition to physical limit switches.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] However, these parameters can often be changed by the operator.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Many CNC tools also do not know anything about their working environment.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Machines may have load sensing systems on spindle and axis drives, but some do not.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] They blindly follow the machining code provided and it is up to an operator to detect if a crash is either occurring or about to occur, and for the operator to manually abort the active process.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Machines equipped with load sensors can stop axis or spindle movement in response to an overload condition, but this does not prevent a crash from occurring.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] It may only limit the damage resulting from the crash.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Some crashes may not ever overload any axis or spindle drives.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] If the drive system is weaker than the machine's structural integrity, then the drive system simply pushes against the obstruction, and the drive motors "slip in place".
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The machine tool may not detect the collision or the slipping, so for example the tool should now be at 210mm on the X-axis, but is, in fact, at 32mm where it hit the obstruction and kept slipping.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] All of the next tool motions will be off by −178mm on the X-axis, and all future motions are now invalid, which may result in further collisions with clamps, vises, or the machine itself.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] This is common in open-loop stepper systems but is not possible in closed-loop systems unless mechanical slippage between the motor and drive mechanism has occurred.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Instead, in a closed-loop system, the machine will continue to attempt to move against the load until either the drive motor goes into an overload condition or a servo motor fails to get to the desired position.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Instead, most hobby CNC tools simply rely on the assumed accuracy of stepper motors that rotate a specific number of degrees in response to magnetic field changes.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] It is often assumed the stepper is perfectly accurate and never missteps, so tool position monitoring simply involves counting the number of pulses sent to the stepper over time.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] An alternate means of stepper position monitoring is usually not available, so crash or slip detection is not possible.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Commercial CNC metalworking machines use closed-loop feedback controls for axis movement.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] In a closed-loop system, the controller monitors the actual position of each axis with an absolute or incremental encoder.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Proper control programming will reduce the possibility of a crash, but it is still up to the operator and programmer to ensure that the machine is operated safely.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Although such simulation is not new, its accuracy and market penetration are changing considerably because of computing advancements.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Within the numerical systems of CNC programming, the code generator can assume that the controlled mechanism is always perfectly accurate, or that precision tolerances are identical for all cutting or movement directions.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] While the common use of ball screws on most modern NC machines eliminates the vast majority of backlash, it still must be taken into account.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] CNC tools with a large amount of mechanical backlash can still be highly precise if the drive or cutting mechanism is only driven to apply cutting force from one direction, and all driving systems are pressed tightly together in that one cutting direction.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] However, a CNC device with high backlash and a dull cutting tool can lead to cutter chatter and possible workpiece gouging.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The backlash also affects the precision of some operations involving axis movement reversals during cutting, such as the milling of a circle, where axis motion is sinusoidal.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] However, this can be compensated for if the amount of backlash is precisely known by linear encoders or manual measurement.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] This is similar to the manual machine tool method of clamping a micrometer onto a reference beam and adjusting the Vernier dial to zero using that object as the reference.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] G-codes are used to command specific movements of the machine, such as machine moves or drilling functions.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The majority of G-code programs start with a percent (%) symbol on the first line, then followed by an "O" with a numerical name for the program (i.e.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] "O0001") on the second line, then another percent (%) symbol on the last line of the program.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The format for a G-code is the letter G followed by two to three digits; for example G01.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] [Code Miscellaneous Functions (M-Code)].
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] M-codes are miscellaneous machine commands that do not command axis motion.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Having the correct speeds and feeds in the program provides for a more efficient and smoother product run.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Incorrect speeds and feeds will cause damage to the tool, machine spindle, and even the product.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The quickest and simplest way to find these numbers would be to use a calculator that can be found online.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] A formula can also be used to calculate the proper speeds and feeds for a material.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] These values can be found online or in Machinery's Handbook.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] The first NC machines were built in the 1940s and 1950s, based on existing tools that were modified with motors that moved the tool or part to follow points fed into the system on punched tape.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] These early servomechanisms were rapidly augmented with analog and digital computers, creating the modern CNC machine tools that have revolutionized machining processes.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] CNC plays an extensive role in the processing manufacturing field, not only the traditional milling and turning, other machines and equipment are also installed with the corresponding CNC, which makes the manufacturing industry in its support, greatly improving the quality and efficiency.
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Traditional subtractive manufacturing can be combined with additive manufacturing (3D printing) to create a new manufacturing method - hybrid additive subtractive manufacturing (HASM).
[src:cnc-machining/numerical-control] Another trend is the combination of AI, using a large number of sensors, with the goal of achieving flexible manufacturing.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Usually the term "turning" is used for cutting *external* surfaces, and "boring" for internal surfaces, or holes.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Thus the phrase "turning and boring" categorizes the larger family of processes known as lathing.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Additionally, "facing" is cutting the ends of the workpiece, to create flat faces.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Turning is typically done with either a manual or computer numerical control (CNC) lathe.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] With a manual lathe, an operator turns cranks to move the cutting tool.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] On a CNC lathe, the cutting tool is moved by a computer, controlling electric motors to follow a pre-programmed path.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Early manual lathes could be used to produce complex geometric figures, even the platonic solids, though this is now usually done with CNC machines.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Different turning processes are typically carried out on a lathe, such as *straight turning*, *taper turning*, *profiling* or *external grooving*.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Those types of turning processes can produce various shapes of materials such as *straight*, *conical*, *curved*, or *grooved* workpieces.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] In general, turning uses simple *single-point cutting* tools.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] The waste metal cut off the workpiece from turning operations are known as chips in North America, or swarf in Britain.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] In some areas they may be known as *turnings*.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] A component that is made by turning is often called a *turned part*.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] The general process of turning involves rotating a workpiece while a single-point cutting tool is moved parallel to the axis of rotation.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Tapered turning produces a cylindrical shape that gradually decreases in diameter from one end to the other.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Spherical generation produces a spherical finished surface by turning a form around a fixed axis of revolution.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] It is generally better than grinding for rough stock removal.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] However, grinding generally produces a better surface finish and can produce parts with greater dimensional accuracy.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Cutting the inside surface of a hole or tube.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] A hole is usually first created by drilling, and then it is bored to enlarge it to its final diameter.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] This process is the reverse of normal drilling operations in that the drill bit is held stationary and the workpiece is rotated.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Reamers can also be used to enlarge a hole after it has been drilled.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] removes material from the end of a workpiece by moving the cutting tool perpendicular to the workpiece's axis of rotation.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Grooving is the cutting of grooves to a specific depth in the workpiece.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] It can be performed on either internal or external surfaces, as well as on the face of the part.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] "Parting off" or "cutoff" is performed by creating a deep groove, all the way through the workpiece, until the end falls off.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Pressing a serrated pattern onto the surface of a part to use as a hand grip or as a visual enhancement using a special purpose knurling tool.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Screw threads can be turned on a lathe using a cutting tool with the shape of the thread.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] The axial movement of the cutting tool is linked to the rotation of the workpiece to create the thread's pitch.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] When this is performed on an outer surface, similar to turning, external threads are created.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] When performed on an internal surface, similar to boring, internal threads are created.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Alternately, taps and dies can be used to cut internal and external threads, respectively.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Turning is usually performed on a lathe, which range in size from tabletop machines suitable for jewelry, to building-sized machines for manufacturing ship propeller shafts.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Chucks grip a workpiece with movable jaws.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] They are less accurate than collets, but can hold a wider range of workpiece sizes.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Collets grip a workpiece by deforming around it.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] They grip over a larger surface than chucks, which puts less pressure on the workpiece, and center the workpiece better.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Each collet has only a narrow range of workpiece diameters that it can deform enough to hold, so large sets of different collets are needed.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] A faceplate is a plate that a workpiece is attached to, often with clamps or t-slot nuts.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] It is often used with a drive dog and mandrel.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] It can hold even more irregularly shaped workpieces than a chuck.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Centers are pointed cones, which support either a hollow tube workpiece, or a workpiece with holes drilled in its ends.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] A drive center is a center which grips the workpiece strongly enough to drive it without the use of a dog.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] They often use hydraulic or spring-loaded teeth that bite into the end of workpieces.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] When supporting a workpiece only with centers, the entire outside of the workpiece may be machined in one setup.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Turning tooling usually cuts with a single point, as opposed to a drill bit or end mill which cut with several sharp edges.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] The angles around the sharp point are important, such as *rake angle*, *side rake angle*, *cutting-edge angle*, and *relief angle*.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Additionally, the cutting point may have a *nose radius* which creates radii when cutting corners in the workpiece and extends the life of the tool tip, but increases machining forces.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] The tool bit is held with a rigid tool holder during operation.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] CNC machines are typically able to switch tools automatically.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Significant forces are required for turning operation, and must be accounted for in the design and selection of the machine tools, the workpiece holding, and any additional supports.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] A setup that is not strong enough may allow the workpiece to break free during operation, ruining the part being made, and endangering the operator.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] A setup that is not rigid enough will deform during operation, and create chatter when cutting, creating an undesirable surface finish, and inaccurate dimensions.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] Speeds and feeds refer to the rotational speed that the workpiece is rotated at, and the feed speed that the tool is moved at.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] They are chosen based on the workpiece material, cutter material, setup rigidity, machine tool rigidity, spindle power, and whether coolant is used.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] The rotational speed is measured in revolutions per minute (rpm).
[src:cnc-machining/turning] The feed rate is the distance that the tool is fed into the workpiece per workpiece revolution.
[src:cnc-machining/turning] It is measured either as millimeters per revolution (mm/rev), or as inches per revolution (in/rev).
